    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Clifton Sunday. 5 o'clock</p>
      <p>I cannot bear not to send you a line, my Dear.</p>
      <p>Tomorrow I shall reply to Herr Kraemer. I have much to say to him in reply; on both the subjects.</p>
      <p>I have misgivings as to his possessing the art of exerting real moral control; &amp; where that is</p>
      <p>not in the power of the instructor, then obedience can only be enforced by a system of continual warfare &amp; punishments; a mode of education I consider fatal, &amp; likewise very wretched for unfortunate children.</p>
      <p>I am now going to the Moravian Meeting. I should have gone yesterday to the Jews' Synagogue, had I not been away. I intend in</p>
      <p>Town to go to all kinds of places of worship.</p>
      <p>I am for seeing &amp; knowing all that is possible. What worlds there are in London, yet unknown to me!--</p>
      <p>Certainly my time never need be wasted there!--</p>
      <p>Return me De la Rive's letter; for in truth I have not yet managed to decipher the whole of it. It is most interesting Can you send the address</p>
      <p>where I am to send the pamphlet? We cannot.--</p>
      <p>Do you see much after the children? You might as well have a little private talk I think with Miss B-- sometimes about them.</p>
    </div></body>
